On this account it was necessary to have tallies both for the sums received on account of blanching ‘¹ and for payments out made without writ. An instance of this is alluded to in the Pipe Roll of 31 Henry 1, when the Earl of Gloucester and Brian Fitz·Count took the accounts of the Treasury of Winchester ὅς and at a later date the Bishop of Carlisle obtained a charter frorn Henry III that his executors should not be impeded in carrying out his will by reason of any such account due from him ⁶. But all this is externa] to the ordinary Exchequer business, and therefore does not appear on the Pipe Rolls, which only exhibit the financial relations betwixt the Treasurer and the accountants ⁷3 and for the same reason it is not directly treated of in the Dialogus.

Such, in brief, was the system by which the money owing to the king throughout the country was collected and accounted for. For further details of its administration we must refer the reader to the printed Pipe Rolls and to Madox’s Hisl073y of the Exchequer.
